<header class="header">
  <h1>What Crops Fail in Short Growing Seasons (And Why)?</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Crop failure in short climates is usually a heat-budget problem.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    In a typical year, frost at <strong>32°F (0°C)</strong> defines the boundary of your growing season.
    In short growing seasons, crops most often fail not because they won’t grow —
    but because they do not accumulate enough heat to mature before frost returns.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Start With the Planning Boundary</h2>

  <p>
    GrowByDate uses 1991–2020 climate normals and frames frost timing at the
    <strong>50% probability level</strong>.
    That means your listed frost dates represent typical-year boundaries — not guarantees.
  </p>

  <p>
    You can determine your frost-free window using the
    <a href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Frost Date Finder</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    But frost-free days alone rarely explain failure.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Why Crops Fail in Short Growing Seasons</h2>

  <p>
    Most short-season crop failures fall into three categories:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Insufficient Growing Degree Days (heat deficit)</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Late fruit ripening relative to first frost</strong></li>
    <li><strong>Cooling nighttime temperatures slowing development</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In nearly every case, the root issue is insufficient heat accumulation before frost returns.
  </p>

  <p>
    (For a deeper explanation of heat modeling, see
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How Frost Dates and Growing Degree Days Work Together</a>.)
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>High-Risk Crops in Short Seasons</h2>

  <h3>1. Long-Season Tomatoes</h3>
  <p>
    Large heirloom tomatoes often require 1,500–1,800+ GDD.
    In short climates, fruit may set but fail to fully ripen before frost.
  </p>

  <h3>2. Late-Season Sweet Corn</h3>
  <p>
    Corn varieties exceeding 85–90 days frequently require higher seasonal heat totals.
    Without sufficient GDD, ear development may remain incomplete.
  </p>

  <h3>3. Winter Squash (Long Varieties)</h3>
  <p>
    Squash requires sustained warmth for fruit maturation and curing.
    Short seasons may interrupt this process before full maturity.
  </p>

  <h3>4. Long-Season Peppers</h3>
  <p>
    Peppers may produce fruit but fail to size up or color fully
    when heat accumulation slows late in the season.
  </p>

  <p>
    In each case, the failure mechanism is similar:
    <strong>seasonal heat accumulation does not meet crop demand.</strong>
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Why “Days to Maturity” Often Misleads</h2>

  <p>
    Seed packets often assume relatively warm growing conditions.
  </p>

  <p>
    In cooler climates, development slows —
    meaning a 90-day crop may take significantly longer.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is explained in
    <a href="/guides/why-days-to-maturity-isnt-enough-in-cold-climates/">Why Days to Maturity Isn’t Enough in Cold Climates</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>How to Predict Failure Before It Happens</h2>

  <p>
    Instead of relying on calendar assumptions, evaluate:
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>First Frost Date → Seasonal Growing Degree Days → Crop Heat Requirement → Risk Margin</strong>
  </p>

  <p>
    You can estimate your seasonal heat budget using the
    <a href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Growing Degree Day Planner</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    If your expected seasonal GDD is well below a crop’s requirement,
    failure becomes likely in a typical year.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Short Seasons Reward Crop Substitution</h2>

  <p>
    In constrained climates, reliability often improves by:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Selecting earlier-maturing varieties</li>
    <li>Choosing lower heat-demand crops</li>
    <li>Reducing reliance on long-season fruiting crops</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Crop substitution usually produces better outcomes
    than attempting to push marginal heat budgets.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>The Failure Pattern in Short Growing Seasons</h2>

  <p>
    Crop failure in short seasons typically follows this sequence:
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Limited Frost-Free Days → Reduced Seasonal GDD → Crop Heat Demand Exceeds Supply → Immature Harvest at First Frost</strong>
  </p>

  <p>
    When heat demand exceeds supply, maturity becomes unlikely in a typical year.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Short growing seasons are constrained by frost at 32°F.</li>
    <li>Frost dates are framed at 50% probability using climate normals.</li>
    <li>Most crop failures in short seasons result from insufficient heat accumulation.</li>
    <li>Long-season fruiting crops carry the highest maturity risk.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In short climates, understanding your seasonal heat budget
    allows you to predict — and prevent — common crop failures.
  </p>
</section>